Across all three models, critical infrastructure sector and method of interaction (primary attack technique) emerged as the most important predictors (see figures 4, 5, and 6). Government and defense sector targeting was the strongest indicator of strategic classification, while commercial sector targeting was most associated with tactical classification. Network infiltration methods skewed strategic, and denial-of-service methods skewed tactical. These findings align with the theoretical expectations that strategic cyber operations tend to target state infrastructure using sophisticated intrusion techniques, while tactical activity resembles criminal patterns in its targeting of private-sector and financial entities through less resource-intensive methods [@peterTypologyStateActors2024; @valerianoCyberStrategy2018]. Objective achievement, damage type, and third-party involvement contributed moderate predictive value, while concession, ransomware, and supply chain showed limited discriminatory power.

