The similar performance across the models shows that the relationship between the predictors and the dependent variable is relatively straightforward and complex methods do not uncover substantially more information or relationships than simpler approaches. The results confirm that the eight predictor variables carry meaningful information about the strategic-tactical distinction because all three models achieved accuracies substantially above the 50% baseline expected from random guessing. The classification is not perfect, with roughly one-third of incidents misclassified across all models. However, the above-baseline performance indicates that strategic cyber operations and tactical cyber activity differ in systematic, observable ways beyond the four primary indicators used to create the dependent variable. The false positive rate of approximately 18% across all models suggests that a meaningful subset of tactical incidents share operational characteristics with strategic operations confirming the idea that the boundary between state-political and state-criminal cyber behavior is blurred [@lavorgnaUnpackingPoliticalcriminalNexus2023].

# Caveats

Several limitations should be considered. First, the two-or-more threshold of the researcher-constructed dependent variable, while grounded in the academic literature and validated against benchmark cases, is an analytical choice, and alternative operationalizations could produce different class assignments. Second, the DCID contains 429 observations, yielding a training set of 301 cases, a modest sample for classification modeling which may contribute to the moderate accuracy levels observed. Third, the dataset is limited to publicly reported and attributed incidents, introducing potential selection bias as covert or undisclosed operations are absent, and included incidents may skew toward higher-profile or more attributable cases. Finally, several predictor variables, namely concession, ransomware, and indirect/immediate damage, have low occurrences, limiting their ability to contribute to classification.

Future research could extend this work in several directions. Incorporating the unstructured political objective text field through natural language processing techniques could capture strategic intent signals that the current structured predictors miss. Applying k-fold cross-validation on the training set, rather than relying solely on a single train-test split, would provide more robust estimates of model performance and reduce sensitivity to the particular random partition [@kohaviCV1995; @hastieElementsStatisticalLearning2009]. Updating the DCID with more current incidents and merging with comparable datasets, such as the European Repository of Cyber Incidents (EuRepoC) or the Council on Foreign Relations (CFR) Cyber Operations Tracker, would create a larger sample and replicating on this larger dataset could test the generalizability of these findings. Also different analytical techniques could be evaluated alongside the three methods used here to uncover different relationships between cyber activity. Most importantly, external validation using an independently coded dataset would strengthen confidence that the strategic-tactical distinction identified in this study reflects genuine empirical patterns rather than artifacts of a single dataset's coding conventions.

