## Decision Tree

The full decision tree was grown with a minimum complexity parameter of 0.001, then pruned using the one standard error (1-SE) rule. The pruned tree selected a complexity parameter of 0.00685 producing an 8-split tree. The decision tree achieved the highest accuracy among the three models at 68.0%, correctly classifying 87 of 128 test set incidents (see table 5) Precision was 67.6% and recall was 72.7%, yielding an F1 score of 0.701 and an AUC of 0.712 (see figure 16. The tree's recall advantage over the other models indicates that it was somewhat better at detecting actual strategic operations while maintaining a comparable false alarm rate.

Variable importance scores from the pruned tree, measured by mean decrease in Gini impurity, identified critical infrastructure sector, method category, and damage type as the most influential predictors in determining split points (see figure 17). The tree visualization shows the set of decision rules making up the classification logic (see figure 18). The root node splits on critical infrastructure sector, classifying government/defense incidents as strategic and routing others to subsequent splits based on method of interaction.

