## Random Forest

The random forest model was tuned by evaluating all eight possible values of mtry, the number of predictors randomly sampled at each split. The optimal mtry was 3, producing a minimum out-of-bag error rate of 31.23% (see figure 19). With 500 trees and the tuned mtry, the random forest achieved an accuracy of 66.4%, matching logistic regression. Precision was 66.2% and recall was 71.2%, yielding an F1 score of 0.691 and an AUC of 0.0718 (see table 6 and figure 20).

Variable importance analysis, measured by both mean decrease in accuracy (how much classification accuracy drops when a predictor's values are randomly permuted) and mean decrease in Gini impurity, identified critical infrastructure sector and method  as the most influential predictors. Critical infrastructure sector and method (primary attack technique) ranked highest on both measures, consistent with the strong bivariate associations observed in the exploratory analysis. Ransomware ranked lowest, reflecting its limited variability in the dataset. (See figure 21.)

